defaultGovernment education reforms, aimed at improving school standards, have led to a
defaultn increasingly autonomous schools system, through conversion of existing schools to Academy status and opening of new schools as Free Schools. These schools have greater freedoms in a variety of areas including whether to expand school places to meet deman
defaultd, decide self-improvement needs and are their own admissions authority.   
default1.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThese reforms have directly led to a decline of the traditional council role in educ
defaultation. Yet, government is clear; local authorities
default as champions of children and parents, with a 
defaultdemocratic mandate, have a responsibility that every school do their best for the local population. Local authorities continue to hold legal duties covering education including to ensure sufficient school places, overall responsibility for school performan
defaultce in the local area and fair access for all children.
default1.3
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultSince 2010, schools that have converted to Academy status have risen from 38 to 185 at secondary level and from 0 to 125 at primary level in the capital. At the same time, more Free Schools have been s
defaultet up in London than in any other part of England. Of the 174 Free Schools opened in England, a total of 58 (34 per cent) are in London. 
